          "body": "The chapter's literary engine is Roman and Jewish *intended* mockery becoming divinely *unintended* truth. The soldiers crown Him with thorns to mock — but Genesis 3:18 named thorns as the curse, and the King is now wearing the curse on His head. They robe Him in purple to mock — but purple is the color of empire, and He IS King. Pilate writes the inscription to humiliate Israel — but it proclaims the gospel in Hebrew (the language of covenant), Latin (the language of power), and Greek (the language of the world). The chief priests object — \"do not write 'The King of the Jews'\" — but Pilate's only resolute act in the chapter is to leave the testimony intact: *what I have written, I have written* (19:22). Every malevolent act is overruled into testimony."
