          "title": "Blood and water — and the eyewitness oath",
          "body": "After Jesus dies, a soldier pierces His side with a spear, and *immediately blood and water came out* (19:34). John interrupts the narrative to insert one of the most striking eyewitness statements in the New Testament: *and he who has seen has testified, and his testimony is true; and he knows that he is telling the truth, so that you also may believe* (19:35). The medical detail — separated blood and clear fluid — corroborates real physical death (likely cardiac rupture or pleural effusion). But John's theological purpose is twofold: (1) refute the docetic claim that Christ only *seemed* to die; (2) seal the fulfillment of Exodus 12:46 (no bone broken) and Zechariah 12:10 (the pierced one). The eyewitness is the same John who writes \"that which we have heard, seen, looked at, and touched\" in 1 John 1:1. The gospel rests on apostolic testimony of a real death."
